  "opinion": "As a woman who’s been working with my hands since I was a child in Naples, I’ve seen how stereotypes can hold people back in ways that aren’t always obvious. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theory—it’s the quiet fear that your identity might make you less capable in a situation where you’re expected to perform well. For me, it’s the worry that my children, who are both smart and curious, might feel that being a woman means they can’t do math or science as well as boys. I’ve heard stories from my own community where girls stop pursuing STEM because they believe they’re not ‘the type’ for it. But addressing this isn’t about fixing people—it’s about changing the environment so that everyone feels they belong. In my carpentry shop, I’ve noticed that when I talk to young women who’re interested in engineering, they often hesitate to ask questions because they fear being judged. That’s stereotype threat in action. We need to create spaces where people feel safe to explore without the weight of expectations. It’s not just about teaching STEM—it’s about teaching respect. My parents taught me that everyone has value, and that belief should be the foundation of how we approach education. In Naples, where we value family and community, we can start by listening to what our children want to do and supporting them without judgment. Stereotype threat is real, but it’s not inevitable. If we focus on creating inclusive environments where everyone feels they belong, we can help young people thrive in STEM without the fear holding them back.",
